STA36835 | Foundations of Statistics Seminar | https://enr-apps.as.cmu.edu/open/SOC/SOCServlet/courseDetails?COURSE=36835&SEMESTER=S19 | instructors:Seidenfeld, Teddy description:In the first phase well examine Savages theory of subjective expected utility chapters 2-5.   Additional readings: Fishburns review, Subjective Expected Utility Theory and Decision, 13 (1981), 131-199; also, Chapters 8 and 13 of Fishburns Utility Theory for Decision Making.    During this part of the course well contrast Savages approach with the von NeumannMorgenstern theory of utility and with the Anscombe-Aumann theory of preferences for horse lotteries.   Also, well discuss some specialized topics, e.g., state-dependent utilities and 5.5, relating to Savages postulate P3.    In the second phase of the course, well focus on the following issues:   1.  A comparison of Savages theory and deFinettis criterion of coherence.   2.  Personal vs. group decisions.   Topics to include: Arrows impossibility theorem, consensus, Savages position in 7.2  13.5.   3.  Violations of the sure-thing principle (Savages postulate P2).  Additional readings will be taken from the psychological and economic literature on (descriptive) models of risk without the expected utility property: Kahneman and Tverskys Prospect Theory, Wakkers Cumulative Prospect Theory, M.Machinas theory, Fishburns SSB theory, etc   For the third phase, well discuss some issues related to Savages chapters 3  4:   4.  Qualitative personal probability (Savages theory without P6) and measurement.   Additional readings on: extensive measurement, definability, elicitation, and scoring rules.  5.  Indeterministic personal probability (Savages theory without P1).  Additional readings on: violations of ordering as in C.A.B.Smiths (1961) theory, and theories of: I.J.Good,  A.P.Dempster (Dempster-Shafer), I.Levi, and T.Fine.   6.   s-additivity and dominance principles (the role of P7 in Savages theory).   Additional readings on conglomerability (deFinetti, Dubins), and on relevant reference sets
